These were generally burned under a cooler prescription.  Grass fuels along the perimeter were too green to burn in April.  A total of 381 acres were blackened during this opertation.  The second phase was an aerial ignition implemented on June 3-4.  This was an aerial ignition.  The majority of this area ia fuel model 1.  There was a total of 10,639 acres available in the unit.  Much of the unit had sparse fuel and rocky soils.

R_COMMENTS: The project area that we are proposing to burn is located 6 miles south of Canjilon. The combination of elevation (8,100) and seasonality make it difficult to obtain good or better ventalation days. In the event that we are limited to fair burning conditions, we are confident that we can insure the safety and Air Quality at current ventalation levels. It is important that we utilize the small window of opportunity to burn during Spring and Fall. Stable weather conditions will allow us to meet the objectives during this burn. It will constitute burning conditions that are easy to maintain and predict. Our winds are predominatly out of the southwest and tend to disburse smoke to the Northeast. This pattern of smoke dispersal creates little or no impact on receptors. Visual moniters will be set in place to analize impacts of smoke wind direction, weather conditions. We also have a contingency plan in the event that smoke dispersal changes direction. We will limit our burn time to minimize effects of diurnal smoke inversion. Dominant fuel type is Sagebrush intermixed with Pinyon Pine. We will be working in the following location: T25N R5E Sec 16,17,19,20,21,25,29,30,31,36.

R_COMMENTS: The b urn will take place in December when there is snow on the ground or there is an abundance of moisture in the air.  This will dramatically limit the fire ability to spread during ignition operations.  As there are homes close to the project area, this would eliminate the concern of having fire spread toward their private property.  If done during warmer months, spread would be a concern and reaction time and options would be limited.This month of the year ususally has periods where fair ventilation catagories exist, but by burning at this time of the year we lesson the stress on the public and the homeowners of the area.The burn will take place in the bottom half of a drainage and residual smoke could be an issue, but mitigation measures such as suppressing (putting out) the piles and ending the ignition process early should help to mitigate these concerns.

R_COMMENTS: The project area that we are proposing to burn is located one mile North of Truchas.  The combination of elevation (8,208) and seasonality makes if difficult to obtain good or better ventilation days.  In the event that we are limited to fair burning conditions, we are confident that we can insure the safety and air quality at lower ventilation levels.  It is important that we utilize the small window of opportunity to burn during the spring and fall.  It will have conditions that are easy to predict and maintain.  Our winds are predominately out of the Southwest and tent to dispurse smoke to the Northeast.  This pattern of smoke dispersal creates no or little impact on Receptors.  We will also have a contigency plan in the event that smoke dispersal changes direction.  We will also limit our burn time to minimize effects of diurnal smlke inversion.

I expect similiar results with only 10% of this total being consumed and producing emissions. This is primarily due to sparse grass cover in most areas.

R_COMMENTS: Burn area is pinon juniper woodlands that has recieved treatment since 1998.  Slash is from range improvement projects which include mechanically pushing trees into piles, watershed improvement projects which basically include that same treatment and or fuelwood utilazation.  Fuelwood permits were issued for pushed material in the piles to encourage utilization of larger material.  Fuelwood units were also set up to harvest green standing and slash is mechanically piled.  Other projects in the area include wildlife habitat improvement where selected windrows or group selection treatments created slash in concentrated areas to facilitate burning.  Objective is to utilize the existing burning window with substantial green-up in non targeted fuels (grass) to reduce the amount of existing slash.  Total project acres is approximately 3,875.

R_COMMENTS: The project area that we are proposing to burn is located one mile North of Truchas.  The combination of elevation (8,208) and seasonality makes if difficult to obtain good or better ventilation days.  In the event that we are limited to fair burning conditions, we are confident that we can insure the safety and air quality at lower ventilation levels.  It is important that we utilize the small window of opportunity to burn during the spring and fall.  It will have conditions that are easy to predict and maintain.  Our winds are predominately out of the Southwest and tent to dispurse smoke to the Northeast.  This pattern of smoke dispersal creates no or little impact on Receptors.  We will also have a contigency plan in the event that smoke dispersal changes direction.  We will also limit our burn time to minimize effects of diurnal smlke inversion.
R_VENTILATION_CATEGORIES: Excellent, Fair, Good, Poor, Very Good

R_NOTIFICATION_PLAN: The burn is close to population centers. The city of Roswell is 4 miles to the WNW. There are residences within a mile radius around the burn site. Critical targets have been identified (Highway 380) within ' miles of the burn perimeter. Smoke production will need to be monitored along this road to ensure visibility. Caution signs will be posted on the road during the burn. The most population is to the west of the burn units. Fuels are predominantly grass and will not result in long term smoke production (smoldering) and residue smoke. The burn plan does not restrict wind direction, but if possible should avoid burning with an east wind. The burn is accessed from refuge roads.  There is no public access into the burn area.

R_COMMENTS: The Jacquez Fire was discovered at 1359 on July 7, 2009.  The fire is being managed by the Cuba Ranger District (Santa Fe NF) as a response to wildland fire confinement - a suppression objective with a confinement strategy. As of today, July 9, 2009; a total of 66 acres have been consumed.  The fire is bounded by Forest Service System roads.  The total number of acres that are possible to be consumed is 750.  This is NOT to say that we plan on burning that many acres; 750 acres represents the total number of acres found within the primary Jacquez Fire planning unit, thus the fire can grow no larger than 750 acres. It was this total number of potential acres that I used to calculate the fuel loading questions found earlier in this form.  Please call if you have any questions,    Tom

R_NOTIFICATION_PLAN: 1.	Two days prior to ignition, Albuquerque Interagency Dispatch Office will be notified. Albuquerque Interagency Dispatch Office will then disseminate burn notifications to the local city, county, state, and federal agencies. Distribution of East Thunderbird Prescribed Burn information packets containing information and maps relevant to the burn to be posted for local residents in Mountainair, Punta De Agua, Manzano, Torreon, Tajique and residents living adjacent to the burn unit. These would contain essential information regarding the prescribed burn process, smoke management, Rx burn terminology, and basic location. This information should include specific guidelines for those people who might have sensitivity to the smoke or other factors relating to the burn. The Mountainair Ranger District should be notified prior to the burn for those individuals requiring special assistance or having any other specific health concerns that might be affected by the burn. Notify appropriate media sources such as the East Mountain Telegraph, the Mountain View Journal and the Independent, 1-2 weeks prior to the burn with a news release. Notices regarding the burn will be posted locally within the east mountain communities of Manzano, Punta De Agua, Torreon, and Tajique. The time frame should be 48-72 hours prior to the burn at the minimum.      Residents living adjacent to the burn area will be contacted by phone or email 24-    	78 hours prior to the burn.  In addition to contacting these individuals signs 	should be posted in the burn vicinity.

This information should include specific guidelines for those people who might have sensitivity to the smoke or other factors relating to the burn. The Mountainair Ranger District should be notified prior to the burn for those individuals requiring special assistance or having any other specific health concerns that might be affected by the burn. Notify appropriate media sources such as the East Mountain Telegraph, the Mountain View Journal and the Independent, 1-2 weeks prior to the burn with a news release. Notices regarding the burn will be posted locally within the east mountain communities of Manzano, Punta De Agua, Torreon, and Tajique. The time frame should be 48-72 hours prior to the burn at the minimum.      Residents living adjacent to the burn area will be contacted by phone or email 24-    	78 hours prior to the burn.  In addition to contacting these individuals signs 	should be posted in the burn vicinity.

R_COMMENTS: The project area that we are proposing to burn is located 5 miles SE from Penasco.  Also burning in section 24. The combination of elevation (8900) and seasonality makes it difficult to obtain good or better ventilation days.  In the event that we are limited to fair burning conditions, we are confident that we can insure the safety and air quality at lower ventilation levels.  It is important that we utilize the small window of opportunity to burn during the spring and fall.  It will have conditions that are easy to predict and maintain.  Our winds are predominately out of the SW and tend to dispurse smoke to the NE.  This pattern of smoke dispersal creates no or little impact on receptors.  Visual monitors will be set in place to monitor impacts of smoke direction, current weather forcasted conditions,  We will also have a contingency plan in the event that smlke dispersal changes direction.  We will also limit our burn time to minimize effects of diurnal smoke inversion.

T_COMMENTS: The burn went better than expected.  It is essentially set up to be a blacklining operation, to eliminate fires started within the Centennial Bombing Range(USAF)from leaving the range and entering the BLM lands adjacent.  Winds actually pulled the ignitions further interior than expected, creating a very secure perimeter for the majority of the range.  Military personnel were very pleased with the outcome, and extended another thank you to AQB for the individual waiver.  We burn here almost every single year, so grass is very light and remote proximity of the bombing range has eliminated smoke issues.

R_NOTIFICATION_PLAN: 1.	Two days prior to ignition, Albuquerque Interagency Dispatch Office will be notified. Albuquerque Interagency Dispatch Office will then disseminate burn notifications to the local city, county, state, and federal agencies. Distribution of East Thunderbird Prescribed Burn information packets containing information and maps relevant to the burn to be posted for local residents in Mountainair, Punta De Agua, Manzano, Torreon, Tajique and residents living adjacent to the burn unit. These would contain essential information regarding the prescribed burn process, smoke management, Rx burn terminology, and basic location. This information should include specific guidelines for those people who might have sensitivity to the smoke or other factors relating to the burn. The Mountainair Ranger District should be notified prior to the burn for those individuals requiring special assistance or having any other specific health concerns that might be affected by the burn. Notify appropriate media sources such as the East Mountain Telegraph, the Mountain View Journal and the Independent, 1-2 weeks prior to the burn with a news release. Notices regarding the burn will be posted locally within the east mountain communities of Manzano, Punta De Agua, Torreon, and Tajique. The time frame should be 48-72 hours prior to the burn at the minimum.      Residents living adjacent to the burn area will be contacted by phone or email 24-    	78 hours prior to the burn.  In addition to contacting these individuals signs 	should be posted in the burn vicinity.

ORG_NAME: Valles Caldera National Preserve - Valles Caldera National Preserve
R_COMMENTS: This is a lightning fire being managed for multiple objectives.  The fire is in a thinning/ burning unit that has been thinned in the past few years, and much of the material has been masticated or removed for commercial use.  Primary objective of the thinning was to restore the natural landscape and prevent high intensity fire.  The primary objective of this burn is to continue with landscape restoration and remove the activity fuels left by the thinning operations.   The unit(s) is surrounded by dirt roads (not open to the public) and the forecast is for a chance of thunderstorms each day.  Fire behavior is anticipated to stay low for the duration of the fire.
R_NOTIFICATION_PLAN:
Initial press release issued 6/27 when fire was at 2 acres.  Planning to issue an updated press release tonight or tomorrow with updated acreage and description of strategies.  Information is also on inciweb, nmfireinfo and the Valles Caldera facebook page.

Thursday, February 25 has good potential for burning given predicted wind direction and speed.  Although poor smoke dispersion is predicted, transport wind direction is away from any population area (i.e., transport wind direction is ESE, SE, SSE) during burn time (11 - 3 p.m.).  Predominant fuel is dormant rangeland grasses.  Recent moisture will increase fuel moisture in 100 and 1000 hour fuels (non-target fuels).  Immediate mop-up will commence following burn.

T_COMMENTS: Burn was an SMPI and only to be 100 acres. Because of the high end of prescription wind and dry fuels, ignition patterns were adjusted to increase safety and reduce the potential for an escape. The new ignition strategy included more of the allowable uplands area. A black line was established off a two-track road to ring the target swale areas. Grass fuels in the uplans were significantly lighter than in the wetland. The 2 grass models are broken out in this form. Winds from the SSW blew smoke away from the population centers (Las Vegas, NM). Had 100% consumption and rapid burn out. Little smoke visible an hour after finishing ignition.

R_NOTIFICATION_PLAN: Two days prior to ignition, Albuquerque Interagency Dispatch Office will be notified. Albuquerque Interagency Dispatch Office will then disseminate burn notifications via email to other Dispatch Centers, county, state, and federal agencies (Regional Office). Distribution of Chato Prescribed Burn information of maps relevant to the burn to be posted for local residents in Mountainair, Punta De Agua, Manzano, Torreon, Tajique and residents living adjacent to the burn unit and/or contacted by phone or email. These would contain essential information regarding the prescribed burn process, smoke management, RX burn terminology, and basic location. This information should include specific guidelines for those people who might have sensitivity to the smoke or other factors relating to the burn. The Mountainair Ranger District should be notified prior to the burn for those individuals requiring special assistance or having any other specific health concerns that might be affected by the burn. Notify appropriate media sources such as the Independent, 1week prior of the burn with a news release. Notices regarding the burn will be posted locally within the east mountain communities of Mountainair, Manzano, Punta De Agua, Torreon, and Tajique. Residents living adjacent to the burn area will be contacted by phone or email 24-78 hours prior to the burn. In addition to contacting these individuals signs should be posted in the burn vicinity.
T_COMMENTS: No acres within Chato RX were burned in 2019!

R_NOTIFICATION_PLAN: Two days prior to ignition, Albuquerque Interagency Dispatch Office will be notified. Albuquerque Interagency Dispatch Office will then disseminate burn notifications via email to other Dispatch Centers, county, state, and federal agencies (Regional Office). Distribution of Chato Prescribed Burn information of maps relevant to the burn to be posted for local residents in Mountainair, Punta De Agua, Manzano, Torreon, Tajique and residents living adjacent to the burn unit and/or contacted by phone or email. These would contain essential information regarding the prescribed burn process, smoke management, RX burn terminology, and basic location. This information should include specific guidelines for those people who might have sensitivity to the smoke or other factors relating to the burn. The Mountainair Ranger District should be notified prior to the burn for those individuals requiring special assistance or having any other specific health concerns that might be affected by the burn. Notify appropriate media sources such as the Independent, 1week prior of the burn with a news release. Notices regarding the burn will be posted locally within the east mountain communities of Mountainair, Manzano, Punta De Agua, Torreon, and Tajique. Residents living adjacent to the burn area will be contacted by phone or email 24-78 hours prior to the burn. In addition to contacting these individuals signs should be posted in the burn vicinity.
T_COMMENTS: No opportunities to burn

T_COMMENTS: We had hoped to complete the small missed portion of our registered burn that had not made the initial registered pass.  Though conditions seemed favorable that morning, the wind shifted directions and the controlled burn was not able to be contained to the registered location and spread into the surrounding areas.  While the fire did what it was suppose to do, burn and restore grasslands- and in that way was successful, it did travel outside the planned area, sometimes jumping long distances or reigniting in areas thought put out.  We were grateful for the support of local fire departments, state police and New Mexico Forestry.

R_COMMENTS: This smoke registration will cover two types of pile burning. The first is to burn most or all of the unit on days with optimal snow cover and good or better ventilation, the second will burn much smaller amounts of piles per day that would qualify for an SMP 1 registration. This approach will dramatically reduce smoke production and can occur on days of a fair or better ventilation category. Once burns are completed I will attach the burn plan that details this approach. After conversations with Rich Naden he suggested that I register this burn for an SMP II registration and use the weekly tracking and notifications to report actual amounts burned.

R_COMMENTS: The project area that we are proposing to burn is located 5 miles SE from Penasco.  The combination of elevation (8900) and seasonality makes it difficult to obtain good or better ventilation days.  In the event that we are limited to fair burning conditions, we are confident that we can insure the safety and air quality at lower ventilation levels.  It is important that we utilize the small window of opportunity to burn during the spring and fall.  It will have conditions that are easy to predict and maintain.  Our winds are predominately out of the SW and tend to dispurse smoke to the NE.  This pattern of smoke dispersal creates no or little impact on receptors.  Visual monitors will be set in place to monitor impacts of smoke direction, current weather forcasted conditions,  We will also have a contingency plan in the event that smlke dispersal changes direction.  We will also limit our burn time to minimize effects of diurnal smoke inversion.

R_COMMENTS: The project area that we are proposing to burn is located 5 miles SE from Penasco.  The combination of elevation (8900) and seasonality makes it difficult to obtain good or better ventilation days.  In the event that we are limited to fair burning conditions, we are confident that we can insure the safety and air quality at lower ventilation levels.  It is important that we utilize the small window of opportunity to burn during the spring and fall.  It will have conditions that are easy to predict and maintain.  Our winds are predominately out of the SW and tend to dispurse smoke to the NE.  This pattern of smoke dispersal creates no or little impact on receptors.  Visual monitors will be set in place to monitor impacts of smoke direction, current weather forcasted conditions,  We will also have a contingency plan in the event that smlke dispersal changes direction.  We will also limit our burn time to minimize effects of diurnal smoke inversion.

T_COMMENTS: Please note: 3 residents within 1 mile of Cottonwood and 1 resident within 1 mile of Publo Creek Ranch were notified of burn days by physical visits or phone calls 1-2 business dyas prior to burning. News release was only other documnet o burning. Road signs were posted as long as any smoke was visible from HWY 180. This burn carried over from 2004 of which one burn day was accomplished and tracking form filled out. This data still reflects 2004 volume as well, but for future reference we will not overlap as such. On 1/25/05 we had a borderline fair/poor ventilation call. Based on the forecast and spot weather called in to this site from dispatch we condidered it fair. We did fill out the visual tracking form for that day and so it is included in this final documenetation. No complaints were received on this day and ignitions took place between 10 am and 2 pm. Burning on this day and in fact the 2 days surrounding this date resulted in fast burning piles with residual smoke being minial at the time of leaving for the day and consumption being over 70% at this time. The following day less than 20% of piles were smoking at all and consumption was at or above 90%. The statewide waiver for pile burning was utilized on this project under fir conditions on 1/25/05 and 2/9/05

R_COMMENTS: The area is located entirely in Chaves County about 6  miles east of Roswell via Highway 380, red bridge and Zinnia Road. The specific area is adjacent to and west of the Bitter Lake National Wildlife Refuge. The purpose for this burn is to consume dead salt cedar that has been excavated and piled. The entire action will improve range and watershed conditions on the Allotment and within the floodplain. The removal of salt cedar is addressed as part of the Roswell Resource Management Plan (October 1997) and within the New mexico Record of Decision dated July 1991 for the vegetation Treatment on BLM Lands in Thirteen States of May 1991.

R_COMMENTS: The project area that we are proposing to burn is located 5 miles SE from Penasco.  The combination of elevation (8900) and seasonality makes it difficult to obtain good or better ventilation days.  In the event that we are limited to fair burning conditions, we are confident that we can insure the safety and air quality at lower ventilation levels.  It is important that we utilize the small window of opportunity to burn during the spring and fall.  It will have conditions that are easy to predict and maintain.  Our winds are predominately out of the SW and tend to dispurse smoke to the NE.  This pattern of smoke dispersal creates no or little impact on receptors.  Visual monitors will be set in place to monitor impacts of smoke direction, current weather forcasted conditions,  We will also have a contingency plan in the event that smlke dispersal changes direction.  We will also limit our burn time to minimize effects of diurnal smoke inversion.

The piles have been placed in a manner to reduce the time spent in pre-ignition/smoldering phases to reduce the amount of smoke being produced.  As piles are consumed they will be chunked together (pushed) to keep the the material burning in the ignition stage rather than the smoldering stage.

R_COMMENTS: Burns in this fuel type in the past have created a natural mosaic pattern due to the variations in fuel types. Ponderosa Pine stands will typically carry fire well with mixed results in the conifer stands and limited effectiveness in the juniper. This usually results in less emmissions than projected due to the acerage that does not burn. Objectives of this project are for restoration of elk and Merriam's turkey habitat and for forest maintenance by reducing hazardous fuel accumulations.

T_COMMENTS:
Approximately 50% of the burn was completed in 2013 and the remainder will be carried over to 2014.  It is requested that the below waiver granted in December 2013 be granted for 2014.

Waiver Granted 
Conditions: Burning is allowed under this waiver under any ventilation conditions from 1 hour after sunrise until 2:00 pm, 7
days a week. The burner shall stop ignitions if smoke begins affecting populations in the communities of Anton Chico or
Villanueva. Public notification shall consist of distributing flyers in the community of Villanueva and in Anton Chico, as well
as notifying neighboring ranchers and fire dispatch centers. An observer shall be stationed on Highway 3 to monitor smoke
impacts. This observer shall take photographs of the smoke during the prescribed burn and submit them to the Air Quality
Bureau as soon as possible. In addition, the observer shall telephone the Air Quality Bureau should smoke begin to affect
the communities of Villanueva and/or Anton Chico. The Air Quality Bureau will attempt to send an observer as well; the
burner shall notify the Air Quality Bureau the day before burning by phone so that we can arrange to send someone to
observe the burn.
Signed by: Rita Bates

R_COMMENTS: These piles are created from El Paso Energy road and well pad clearing (they own the oil/gas rights - so we have only limited control over their actions).  El Paso does pay approximately $100,000 per year in contracting a Hydro-Axe to mulch non-merchantable trees.  All useable portions of merchanatable trees are turned into sawlogs or post logs and removed from site.  These two actions severely reduce the total potential smoke emissions if we burned all wood removed from roads and well pads - our best estimate is that this is a 70% reduction in fuels and subsequently emissions.  Additionally, these piles are scattered across almost half of our property or 250,000 acres and they are scattered by the fact that they are roads rather than contiguous treatment areas.  Accordingly, we have broken up the piles into burn units/registrations which make sense on the ground.

R_COMMENTS: The b urn will take place in December when there is snow on the ground or there is an abundance of moisture in the air.  This will dramatically limit the fire ability to spread during ignition operations.  As there are homes close to the project area, this would eliminate the concern of having fire spread toward their private property.  If done during warmer months, spread would be a concern and reaction time and options would be limited.This month of the year ususally has periods where fair ventilation catagories exist, but by burning at this time of the year we lesson the stress on the public and the homeowners of the area.The burn will take place in the bottom half of a drainage and residual smoke could be an issue, but mitigation measures such as suppressing (putting out) the piles and ending the ignition process early should help to mitigate these concerns.

I have listed 500 acres per day as the maximum acreage per day in the unlikely event that burning implementation goes so smoothly and smoke dispersal is so excellent that the entire project may be completed in one day.  It is unlikely, but not entirely improbable.  What is more likely to be the case, is we will only burn several hundred acres per day until project is completed.  

Also, this form only allows one section to be listed, but this project encompasses parts of 4 sections - 2, 3, 10, 11.

Also, I listed all times of year expected to burn (even though it is the end of August now) in the event that we do not get an opportunity to implement this fall and must roll this project over to next year.

R_COMMENTS: Cinders from ACI accidentally ignited nearby slash/pine needles after COB on 8/13/08. Fire Department(FD) notified about smoke, called Public Works Dept. at approx 5:40pm. FD personnel responded, as did Solid Waste personnel. Isolated burning materials from non burning, and pumped water onto fire and wet adjacent materials until approx 10:00pm. PW Director checked status at 4:00am, noted no spreading, but still smoldering pine needles. Backhoe used in slash pit damaged during operations, part ordered early 8/14, to be installed 8/15. Plan to continue to apply water by FD personnel and move materials with backhoe as soon as repaired.

R_COMMENTS: The intent of this project is to only burn the understory of the standing live and dead juniper to kill seedlings and young juniper.  Actual fuel load is closer to 0.30 tons/acre for all 492 acres, however because of the slim possibility of a mature stand ignition I have entered the entire possible fuel load.  In 2003, a similar burn was performed with a higher grass fuel load (closer to 0.70 tons/acre) and the mature stand would not ignite.

R_COMMENTS: Upper Rio Bonito is a WUI project in the Fort Stanton ACEC located NE of Ruidoso NM which is located 11 miles SW of the burn area. Smaller subdivisions are located between Ruidoso and the burn unit to the SW the closest being Raches of Sonterra that is within 1.5 miles W of the burn area. The White Mountain Wilderness Area is located 7 miles WSW of the burn area and is not likely to receive any impacts from smoke. Sierra Blanca airport is located 1.5 miles to the SE of the burn unit. Burning is scheduled to be conducted when snow or moisture is or has been received in the area. This allows piles to be burned down with minimal chance for escape. Roads are signed entering into the project area with control burn signs and public notifications are made through the media. Piles have cured for 1 seasons. All 1000 hr fuels and larger have been removed. Piles consist of 100 hr fuels or smaller. Piles are covered. Fuel loading was estimated by pile size 48" x 8' x 8' = 3072 in. div/12 = 256 cf per pile x 15 piles per acre x 75 acres. These piles typically burn down in less than one hours time and are out within 24 horus.

BURN_NAME: Pecos River Pile Burn/West Overflow wetlands ACEC
R_COMMENTS: The area is located entirely in Chaves County within the BLM designated Overflow Wetlands Area of Critical Environmental Concern (ACEC). The project is about 16 miles east of Roswell and south of Bottomless Lakes State Park. The purpose for this burn is to consume dead salt cedar that has been excavated and piled. The entire action will improve riparian conditions along the Pecos River. The removal of salt cedar is addresses as part of the Roswell Resource Management Plan (October 1997) and within the New Mexico Record of Decision dated July 1991 for the Vegetation Treatment on BLM Lands in Thirteen States of May 1991.

R_COMMENTS: Airport Mesa is a WUI project in the Fort Stanton ACEC located NE of Ruidoso NM which is located 10 miles SW of the burn area. Smaller subdivisions are located between Ruidoso and the burn unit to the SW the closest being Raches of Sonterra that is within 1.5 miles NW of the burn area. The White Mountain Wilderness Area is located 7  miles WNW of the burn area and is not likely to receive any impacts from smoke. Sierra Blanca Airport is located 1.5 miles to the NE of the burn unit. Smoke direction will be monitored at all times to ensure no impacts will affect the airport. Burning is scheduled to be conducted when snow or moisture is or has been received in the area. This allows piles to be burned down with minimal chance for escape. Roads are signed entering into the project area with control burn signs and public notifications are made through the media. Piles have cured for 1 seasons. All 1000 hr fuels and larger have been removed. Piles consist of 100 hr fuels or smaller. Piles are covered. Fuel loading was estimated by pile size 48" x 8' x 8' = 3072 in. div/12 - 256 cf per pile x 15 piles per acre x 197 acres. These piles typically burn down in less than one hour time and are out within 24 hours.

R_NOTIFICATION_PLAN: Two days prior to ignition, Albuquerque Interagency Dispatch Office will be notified. Albuquerque Interagency Dispatch Office will then disseminate burn notifications via email to other Dispatch Centers, county, state, and federal agencies (Regional Office). Distribution of Chato Prescribed Burn information of maps relevant to the burn to be posted for local residents in Mountainair, Punta De Agua, Manzano, Torreon, Tajique and residents living adjacent to the burn unit and/or contacted by phone or email. These would contain essential information regarding the prescribed burn process, smoke management, RX burn terminology, and basic location. This information should include specific guidelines for those people who might have sensitivity to the smoke or other factors relating to the burn. The Mountainair Ranger District should be notified prior to the burn for those individuals requiring special assistance or having any other specific health concerns that might be affected by the burn. Notify appropriate media sources such as the Mountain View Telegraph and the Independent, 1week prior of the burn with a news release. Notices regarding the burn will be posted locally within the east mountain communities of Mountainair, Manzano, Punta De Agua, Torreon, and Tajique. The time frame should be 48-72 hours prior to the burn at the minimum. Residents living adjacent to the burn area will be contacted by phone or email 24-78 hours prior to the burn.  In addition to contacting these individuals signs should be posted in the burn vicinity.

R_COMMENTS: The area is located entirely in Chaves County about 6  miles east of Roswell via Highway 380, red bridge and Zinnia Road. The specific area is adjacent to and west of the Bitter Lake National Wildlife Refuge. The purpose for this burn is to consume dead salt cedar that has been excavated and piled. The entire action will improve range and watershed conditions on the Allotment and within the floodplain. The removal of salt cedar is addressed as part of the Roswell Resource Management Plan (October 1997) and within the New mexico Record of Decision dated July 1991 for the vegetation Treatment on BLM Lands in Thirteen States of May 1991.

R_COMMENTS: The purpose of this burning is to remove activity slash from a fuel break placed around Urban Interface. Visual monitoring of smoke dispersion and ventilation tracking will take place on days of ignition regardless of ventilation category.  Smoke dispersion will be monitored visually and ignition will cease if residences or Highway 32 are impacted, even in Good or better ventilation categories.  In parts of burn units, removal of pinyon, oak, and juniper was completed.  In other parts of burn units, mechanical chipping of material was employed.  The remaining material was inaccessible due to rugged and steep terrain.  The maximum daily pile volume was entered as 20,000 cubic feet, but we expect to burn between 10,000 and 20,000 cubic feet per day. Distribution of Chato Prescribed Burn information of maps relevant to the burn to be posted for local residents in Mountainair, Punta De Agua, Manzano, Torreon, Tajique and residents living adjacent to the burn unit and/or contacted by phone or email. These would contain essential information regarding the prescribed burn process, smoke management, RX burn terminology, and basic location. This information should include specific guidelines for those people who might have sensitivity to the smoke or other factors relating to the burn. The Mountainair Ranger District should be notified prior to the burn for those individuals requiring special assistance or having any other specific health concerns that might be affected by the burn. Notify appropriate media sources such as the Mountain View Telegraph and the Independent, 1week prior of the burn with a news release. Notices regarding the burn will be posted locally within the east mountain communities of Mountainair, Manzano, Punta De Agua, Torreon, and Tajique. The time frame should be 48-72 hours prior to the burn at the minimum. Residents living adjacent to the burn area will be contacted by phone or email 24-78 hours prior to the burn.  In addition to contacting these individuals signs should be posted in the burn vicinity.

R_COMMENTS: Bonito Bench 1 is a WUI project in the Fort Stanton ACEC located NE of Ruidoso NM which is located 11 miles SW of the burn area. Smaller subdivisions are located between Ruidoso and the burn unit to the SW the closest being Rnaches of Sonterra that is wit hin 1.5 miles of the burn area. The White Mountain Wilderness Area is located WSW of the burn area and is not likely to receive any impacts from smoke. Sierra Blanca Airport is located 1.5 miles to the SE of the burn unit. Burning is scheudled to b conducted when snow or moisture is or has been received in the area. This allows piles to be burned down with minimal chance for escape. Roads are signed entering into the project area with control burn signs and public notifications are made through the media. Piles have cured for 2 seasons. All 1000 hour fuels and larger have been removed. Piles consist of 100 hr fuels or smaller. Piles are covered. Fuel loading was estimated by pile size 48" x 8' x 8' = 3072 in. div/12 = 265 cf per pile x 15 piles per acre x 185 acres. These piles typically burn down in less than one hours time and are out within 24 hours.

The area is located entirely in Chaves County about 6  miles east of Roswell via Highway 380, red bridge and Zinnia Road. The specific area is adjacent to and west of the Bitter Lake National Wildlife Refuge. The purpose for this burn is to consume dead salt cedar that has been excavated and piled. The entire action will improve range and watershed conditions on the Allotment and within the floodplain. The removal of salt cedar is addressed as part of the Roswell Resource Management Plan (October 1997) and within the New mexico Record of Decision dated July 1991 for the vegetation Treatment on BLM Lands in Thirteen States of May 1991.

R_COMMENTS: The project area that we are proposing to burn is located 5 miles SE from Penasco.  Also burning in section 24. The combination of elevation (8900) and seasonality makes it difficult to obtain good or better ventilation days.  In the event that we are limited to fair burning conditions, we are confident that we can insure the safety and air quality at lower ventilation levels.  It is important that we utilize the small window of opportunity to burn during the spring and fall.  It will have conditions that are easy to predict and maintain.  Our winds are predominately out of the SW and tend to dispurse smoke to the NE.  This pattern of smoke dispersal creates no or little impact on receptors.  Visual monitors will be set in place to monitor impacts of smoke direction, current weather forcasted conditions,  We will also have a contingency plan in the event that smlke dispersal changes direction.  We will also limit our burn time to minimize effects of diurnal smoke inversion.

R_COMMENTS: Burns in this fuel type in the past have created a natural mosaic pattern due to the variations in fuel types. Ponderosa Pine stands will typically carry fire well with mixed results in the conifer stands and limited effectiveness in the juniper. This usually results in less emmissions than projected due to the acerage that does not burn. Objectives of this project are for restoration of elk and Merriam

R_COMMENTS: The project area that we are proposing to burn is located 5 miles SE from Penasco.  The combination of elevation (8900) and seasonality makes it difficult to obtain good or better ventilation days.  In the event that we are limited to fair burning conditions, we are confident that we can insure the safety and air quality at lower ventilation levels.  It is important that we utilize the small window of opportunity to burn during the spring and fall.  It will have conditions that are easy to predict and maintain.  Our winds are predominately out of the SW and tend to dispurse smoke to the NE.  This pattern of smoke dispersal creates no or little impact on receptors.  Visual monitors will be set in place to monitor impacts of smoke direction, current weather forcasted conditions,  We will also have a contingency plan in the event that smlke dispersal changes direction.  We will also limit our burn time to minimize effects of diurnal smoke inversion.

R_COMMENTS: Burn area is pinon juniper woodlands that has recieved treatment since 1998.  Slash is from range improvement projects which include mechanically pushing trees into piles, watershed improvement projects which basically include that same treatment and or fuelwood utilazation.  Fuelwood permits were issued for pushed material in the piles to encourage utilization of larger material.  Fuelwood units were also set up to harvest green standing and slash is mechanically piled.  Other projects in the area include wildlife habitat improvement where selected windrows or group selection treatments created slash in concentrated areas to facilitate burning.  Objective is to utilize the existing burning window with substantial green-up in non targeted fuels (grass) to reduce the amount of existing slash.  Total project acres is approximately 3,875.

R_COMMENTS: Boundary pile burn unit is a 25 mile long loop WUI project. The remaining limbs and heavier logs were windrowed in piles that are approximately 2x3x8-100'. The windrows are not continous for the entire 25 miles. I used 2x3x5280(12) divided by 3 as the piles are triangle shaped to estimate entire pile volume. Planned start date is 3/15/04. Piles are approximately two years old. The burn is in the westeren closed air shed. Approximately 2/3 of the project area in isolated hard to access country and actual emissions will most likely be lower per day in those areas.

R_NOTIFICATION_PLAN: Prior to ignition, Albuquerque Interagency Dispatch Office will be notified. Albuquerque Interagency Dispatch Office will then disseminate burn notifications via email to other Dispatch Centers, county, state, and federal agencies (Regional Office). Distribution of Chato Prescribed Burn information of maps relevant to the burn to be posted for residents in Mountainair, Punta De Agua, Manzano, Torreon, Tajique and residents living adjacent to the burn unit and/or contacted by phone or email. These would contain essential information regarding the prescribed burn process, smoke management, RX burn terminology, and basic location. This information should include specific guidelines for those people who might have sensitivity to the smoke or other factors relating to the burn. The Mountainair Ranger District should be notified prior to the burn for those individuals requiring special assistance or having any other specific health concerns that might be affected by the burn. Notify appropriate media sources such as the Independent, 1 week prior of the burn with a news release. Notices regarding the burn will be posted locally within the east mountain communities of Mountainair, Manzano, Punta De Agua, Torreon, and Tajique. The time frame should be 48-72 hours prior to the burn at the minimum. Residents living adjacent to the burn area will be contacted by phone or email 24-78 hours prior to the burn.  In addition to contacting these individuals‚Äô signs should be posted in the burn vicinity.

R_COMMENTS: This smoke registration will cover two different potential approaches to burning the piles in the unit. The first is to burn the entire unit and all the piles at once with ample snow on the ground and good or better ventilation and winds that reduce the impacts of smoke on the Freeway. The second approach will be to burn a much smaller number of piles per day, amounts that would qualify for a SMP I registration, on days when snow cover is not available. This will dramatically reduce smoke impacts and burning on these days can occur with a fair or better ventilation category. Once they are completed I will attach the two burn plans that cover these strategies in detail. After conversations with Rich Naden, he suggested that I file for the SMP II registrations for both strategies and use weekly tracking and notifications to report actual amounts burned.

R_COMMENTS: The project area that we are proposing to burn is located 2 miles east of canon Plaza, 5 miles NW of Petaca and 5 miles north of Vallecitos. The combination of elevvation 8,300 and seasonality make it difficult to obtain a good or better ventilation. In the vent tht we are limited to fair burning conditions we are confident that we can insure the safety and air quality regulaitons for PM 10 at lower ventilation levels. It is important that we utilize the small window of opportunity to burn during the sping and fall. Stable weather conditions will allow us to meet the objectives during this burn. It will constitute burning conditions that are easy to maintain and predict. Our winds are predomintly out of the SW and tend to disburse the smoke to the NE. This pattern of smoke dispersal creates no or little impact on receptores. Visual monitors will be set in place to monitor impacts of smoke wind direction, current weather forecasted conditions. We wll also have a contingency plan in the event that smoke dispersal changes direction. We will also limit our burn time to minimize effects of diurnal smoke inversion.

R_COMMENTS: The project area that we are proposing to burn is located 5 miles SE from Penasco.  Also burning in section 24. The combination of elevation (8900) and seasonality makes it difficult to obtain good or better ventilation days.  In the event that we are limited to fair burning conditions, we are confident that we can insure the safety and air quality at lower ventilation levels.  It is important that we utilize the small window of opportunity to burn during the spring and fall.  It will have conditions that are easy to predict and maintain.  Our winds are predominately out of the SW and tend to dispurse smoke to the NE.  This pattern of smoke dispersal creates no or little impact on receptors.  Visual monitors will be set in place to monitor impacts of smoke direction, current weather forcasted conditions,  We will also have a contingency plan in the event that smlke dispersal changes direction.  We will also limit our burn time to minimize effects of diurnal smoke inversion.

R_NOTIFICATION_PLAN: Prior to ignition, Albuquerque Interagency Dispatch Office will be notified. Albuquerque Interagency Dispatch Office will then disseminate burn notifications via email to other Dispatch Centers, county, state, and federal agencies (Regional Office). Distribution of Capilla Piles Prescribed Burn information of maps relevant to the burn to be posted for residents in Mountainair, Punta De Agua, Manzano, Torreon, Tajique and residents living adjacent to the burn unit and/or contacted by phone or email. These would contain essential information regarding the prescribed burn process, smoke management, RX burn terminology, and basic location. This information should include specific guidelines for those people who might have sensitivity to the smoke or other factors relating to the burn. The Mountainair Ranger District should be notified prior to the burn for those individuals requiring special assistance or having any other specific health concerns that might be affected by the burn. Notify appropriate media sources such as the Independent, 1 week prior of the burn with a news release. Notices regarding the burn will be posted locally within the east mountain communities of Mountainair, Manzano, Punta De Agua, Torreon, and Tajique. The time frame should be 48-72 hours prior to the burn at the minimum. Residents living adjacent to the burn area will be contacted by phone or email 24-78 hours prior to the burn. In addition to contacting these individuals‚Äô signs should be posted in the burn vicinity.
